**Elasticsearch version**: 5.0

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:

If I have a document with an ip address field with value of 192.168.0.255, I can query for it using CIDR 192.168.0.0/24, and get a hit on the document:
```
{
  "query": {
    "term": { "address": "192.168.0.0/24" }
  }
}

```
However, if I do an IP range aggregation on that subnet, then this document is not included, i.e.:
```
{
  "size": 0,
  "aggregations" : {
    "networks": {
      "ip_range": {
            "field": "addresses",
            "ranges": [
              { "mask" : "192.168.0.0/24" }  
            ]
      }
    }
  }
}
```

That is because on generic range aggregations the `to` value is exclusive, as documented here:
https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/search-aggregations-bucket-range-aggregation.html

In fact, if you aggregate using a /32 CIDR, you'll never get a hit on the IP address itself, which is even more poignant, i.e., 192.168.0.1 address value will not be aggregated inside 192.168.0.1/32. The same holds if you aggregate for range from 192.168.0.1 to 192.168.0.1; such an aggregation will always have a count of 0.

I suppose I can understand that `to` is exclusive for other types of ranges, but for a CIDR range I would not expect that behavior. 192.168.0.255 is definitely in the 192.168.0.0/24 subnet. I would also expect consistent behavior for querying and aggregating a subnet.

Thanks.

